    <text>
        <body>
            <head>199. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in Tunisia<note n="1"
                    place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d199fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                    Central Foreign Policy File, D790135–0993. Confidential; Priority. Sent for
                    information Priority to Tripoli. Drafted by Pudschun; cleared in <gloss
                        target="#t_NEAAFN_1">NEA/AFN</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_NEA_1">NEA</gloss>,
                    M/CT, EB, and D; approved by <persName corresp="recIEUqCutc3qMOCv"
                        >Newsom</persName>.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1979-03-24T00:00:00+00:00">March 24, 1979, 0000Z</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>73047. Subject: Ambassador <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName>’s
                Call on Under Secretary <persName corresp="recIEUqCutc3qMOCv">Newsom</persName>
                March 20.</p>
            <p>1. (C) Entire text.</p>
            <p>2. Prior to his departure for <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                    >Tunisia</placeName> to participate in the <orgName corresp="recHh5Ro1Ueoi84PG"
                    >Joint Commission</orgName> meeting, Ambassador <persName
                    corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName> called on Under Secretary <persName
                    corresp="recIEUqCutc3qMOCv">Newsom</persName>. The Ambassador raised three main
                issues: (a) <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisian</placeName> expectations
                that there will be a substantial increase in U.S. assistance to <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName> as a result of the highly
                successful <persName corresp="rec8IOwPGGW4LB0wR">Nouira</persName> visit and the
                    <orgName corresp="recHh5Ro1Ueoi84PG">Joint Commission</orgName> meeting; (b) the
                    <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1979 and 1980 reduction in <gloss
                    target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> credits for <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>; and
                (c) the possible sale of Boeing 747s to <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libya</placeName> as reported in the U.S. press.<note n="2" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d199fn2">In a March 3 article in the <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                        <rs type="work" corresp="recSkppmEfvArrEDE">Washington Post</rs>
                    </hi>, the <orgName corresp="recLsDdFBv66740Gh">Associated Press</orgName>
                    reported that <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> was
                    granted permission to purchase three Boeing 747s and two <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="reccFysHaUEN9EX4w">Boeing 727s</rs>. (“State Dept. Approves Sale of
                    Jumbo Jets to Libya,” <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                        <rs type="work" corresp="recSkppmEfvArrEDE">Washington Post</rs>
                    </hi>, March 3, 1979, p. A6)</note>
            </p>
            <p>3. Ambassador <persName corresp="recIEUqCutc3qMOCv">Newsom</persName> began by noting
                that the U.S. has spoken of phasing out aid to <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName> for a number of years, but for
                valid reasons we have committed ourselves to assistance through the end of the
                current five-year plan. Through the <orgName corresp="recHh5Ro1Ueoi84PG">Joint
                    Commission</orgName> meeting and with the participation of Mrs. <persName
                    corresp="recVgLVPXRruS2DSE">Kreps</persName>, we hope to move into an effective
                relationship built on trade and investment. Although he did not exclude the
                possibility of further <rs type="topic" corresp="recm5bcRb25jCek8u">economic
                    assistance</rs>, <persName corresp="recIEUqCutc3qMOCv">Newsom</persName>
                indicated that the U.S. would like to use the <orgName corresp="recHh5Ro1Ueoi84PG"
                    >Joint Commission</orgName> meeting as a vehicle to find other ways to
                cooperate. <persName corresp="recoJB3QsHSMqYcVi">Bishop</persName> mentioned the
                possibility of <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="rec2aKcvf5fqVhzHt">
                    <gloss target="#t_PL_1">PL</gloss> 480</rs> funds after 1981. <persName
                    corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName> noted that the Secretary <pb
                    facs="0502" n="481" xml:id="pg_481"/> had been encouraging about additional
                assistance for the central <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                    >Tunisia</placeName> rural development project during the <persName
                    corresp="rec8IOwPGGW4LB0wR">Nouira</persName> visit.<note n="3" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d199fn3">Telegram 305925 to Tunis, December 3, summarized <persName
                        corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Vance</persName>’s November 30 luncheon meeting
                    with <persName corresp="rec8IOwPGGW4LB0wR">Nouira</persName>. (National
                    Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File, D780497–0969)</note> He also said
                that aid levels to <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName> are
                ridiculously low when compared to aid figures recently publicized in the press.
                    <persName corresp="recIEUqCutc3qMOCv">Newsom</persName> concluded the discussion
                of aid levels by noting that he had never before this year of extreme budgetary
                constraint seen senior <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">U.S.
                    Government</rs> officials dealing with allocations of such modest amounts of
                money.</p>
            <p>4. In response to <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName>’s remarks on
                    <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> credit to <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>,
                    <persName corresp="recIEUqCutc3qMOCv">Newsom</persName> indicated that he hoped
                the 10 million dols reinstated by the <persName corresp="reciVaIjLqblMmInB"
                    >Solarz</persName> subcommittee would be sustained but that, in any case, we
                would try to provide in future years the total figure mentioned by then Under
                Secretary <persName corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName> in 1976.<note n="4"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d199fn4">See <ref target="frus1969-76ve09p1#d124">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, vol. E–9,
                        Part 1, Documents on North Africa, 1973–1976, Document 124</ref>.</note>
            </p>
            <p>5. Finally, Ambassador <persName corresp="recIEUqCutc3qMOCv">Newsom</persName>
                indicated that the issue of selling 747s to <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libya</placeName> remains under study. We sold the Libyans <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="reccFysHaUEN9EX4w">727s</rs> with the understanding that they would not
                be used for military purposes. If it were proven that the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="reccFysHaUEN9EX4w">727s</rs> were now being used in <placeName
                    corresp="recQS1Cl4Z2PTsUiY">Uganda</placeName>, it would affect our decision as
                to whether or not to sell 747s to <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libya</placeName>. In any case, the situation is far from settled. <persName
                    corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName> asked whether this proposed sale
                indicated any change in <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName>
                policy or in U.S. policy toward <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libya</placeName>. He also noted that 747s are too big to be used commercially
                in <placeName corresp="reco2M6RfIym93BJO">North Africa</placeName>. <persName
                    corresp="recIEUqCutc3qMOCv">Newsom</persName> responded that the situation with
                    <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> is a difficult one for
                the U.S. Although the Libyans have made several approaches to the U.S. in an effort
                to improve <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recRtTKQqtxKMBMhV">relations</rs>,
                to the extent <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> supports
                international <rs type="topic" corresp="rec1Zl9FOvMzxLARV">terrorism</rs>, it will
                be very difficult to normalize <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recRtTKQqtxKMBMhV">relations</rs>. In response to a question from
                    <persName corresp="recIEUqCutc3qMOCv">Newsom</persName>, <persName
                    corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName> indicated that <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName> sees little, if any, change in
                    <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> policy.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Vance</hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
